MARPOL Annex I — Oily-water Separating Equipment and Bilge Water Discharge (Regulations 14–15).

Regulation 14 — Oily-water separating and oil filtering equipment:
Ships of 400 GT and above shall be fitted with oily-water separating equipment (OWS) capable of producing effluent with oil content not exceeding 15 parts per million (ppm). An Oil Content Monitor (OCM/OMD) must be fitted to automatically stop overboard discharge when the oil content exceeds 15 ppm and activate an alarm.

Regulation 15 — Control of discharge of oil:
Discharge of bilge water from machinery spaces is ONLY permitted when ALL of the following conditions are met:
• The ship is proceeding en route (not at anchor or in port);
• The oil content of the effluent does not exceed 15 ppm;
• The ship has in operation an OWS and an oil content meter fitted with a recording device;
• The ship is not within a special area.

No discharge is permitted whatsoever in special areas (Mediterranean, Baltic, Black Sea, Red Sea, Gulfs Area, Gulf of Aden, Antarctic, North West European Waters, Oman Sea, South South African Waters).

MARPOL Annex I — Oil Record Book Part I (Machinery Space Operations) — Regulation 17.

Every ship of 400 GT and above must maintain an Oil Record Book (ORB) Part I.

Entries must be made for:
• Ballasting or cleaning of fuel oil tanks;
• Discharge of dirty ballast or cleaning water from fuel oil tanks;
• Collection, transfer or discharge of oil residues (sludge);
• Discharge overboard or disposal of bilge water from machinery spaces (including OWS operations);
• Transfer to reception facility;
• Accidental or other exceptional discharges of oil;
• OWS operational condition and any malfunctions.

Each entry must be signed by the officer in charge of the operation, and each completed page must be countersigned by the master.

The ORB must be kept on board the vessel and be readily available for inspection by the Administration at any time. It must be retained for a period of three years after the last entry.
